    Date: Mon, 8 Feb 88 12:53 EST
    From: David C. Plummer &lt;DCP@QUABBIN.SCRC.Symbolics.COM&gt;

    ...

    Assuming MIT isn't going to get more recent domain code on their
    machines, how should I kludge my code to know to expect this lossage and
    deal with it appropriately?  Should I use the part of the answer they
    gave me (without the NS records)?  That doesn't quite work because the
    authoritative bit isn't set.  Should I special case MIT as losing and
    pretend it gives authoritative no-answer messages?  I'd like to be
    liberal in what I accept, but I can't figure out how to do it.  (Fixing
    the machines at MIT would be better, of course.)


We just yesterday installed a new version of the nameserver on our machines,
Berkeley UNIX bind version 4.7.3, that is supposed to work better.  It would
be interesting to know if it fixes the problems that you have pointed out.  We
have very little understanding of how the program works, and are trying real
hard to stay out of the hacking-of-somebody-elses-domain-code buisness.
Originally we were going to wait for the official "released' version of bind,
but it always seems to be just a few weeks away, so we gave up and just went
ahead and installed the beta test version.

